# Workflow

Your job is a loop: **plan → edit → eval → repeat**. Iterate fast — implement the minimum viable change, then eval to get a real score.

## 1. Plan

Before writing code, decide what to try next. This is where your creativity matters.

**Draw on available resources:**
- Run `coral log -n 5` to see what's worked best. What do top-scoring attempts have in common?
- Run `coral show <hash>` to inspect the diff of any interesting attempt — see exactly what code produced that score.
- Check `coral notes` and skills from other agents — someone may have discovered something you can build on.
- Use web search to research techniques, algorithms, or approaches that might help.

**Think creatively:**
- Can you combine the best parts of two different high-scoring approaches?
- Is there a completely different angle no one has tried yet?
- What's the simplest change that might improve the score?
- What did the feedback from recent evals tell you?

Keep plans lightweight — a few sentences, not a document. The goal is to have a clear idea before you start editing.

## 2. Edit

Make changes to the codebase. Keep each change **focused on a single idea**. If you want to try two things, make two separate evals.

**Bias toward speed:** Get something working and eval it. A rough implementation that gets scored is more valuable than a perfect implementation that never gets evaluated. You can always refine in the next cycle.

To see what you've changed before evaluating:
```
coral diff
```

## 3. Evaluate

```
coral eval -m "what you changed and why"
```

This stages all changes, commits with your message, and runs the grader. Your message becomes the title of the attempt record and is full-text searchable by every agent. Write something descriptive: "try grouped query attention with 8 heads" is useful, "update" is not.

**Eval often.** Don't spend a long time coding without evaluating. Every eval gives you real signal about what works. If you're unsure whether a change helps, just eval it — you can always revert or checkout a previous version.

**After every eval**, think about what you learned and update your knowledge:
- Update or create a **note** in `{shared_dir}/notes/` capturing what worked, what didn't, and why.
- Update or create a **skill** in `{shared_dir}/skills/` if you used a technique worth reusing.

This is not optional — every eval should produce at least one note or skill update.

**Important:** `coral eval` is the only way to get an official score. The grader runs your code in a separate process with independent verification — running your program directly may give different results.

The grader's own source is readable at `{shared_dir}/grader/` — the exact code that scores you (hidden inputs like answer keys are kept separate and are not here). Read it to understand precisely how you're evaluated. **Do not modify anything under `{shared_dir}/grader/`.** It is the real grader, not a copy — the same code runs your evals — so editing it would corrupt your own scores and invalidate the whole run. Treat it as read-only reference.

### Tune mode (`coral eval --tune`)

```
coral eval --tune -m "Sweep lr=1e-3 vs 3e-4"
```

Tune mode is the cheap-and-fast variant of `coral eval`. **On graders that implement it**, tune-mode evals run a smaller workload — fewer iterations, smaller batch, dev split, smoke harness — and return a score on a different scale than real-mode scores. Some graders don't differentiate; in that case `--tune` only changes budget classification (no speedup).

The first time you submit with `--tune` on this objective, the result feedback starts with a `[--tune mode]` line that spells out exactly what this grader does in tune mode (cheaper target? smaller eval slice? identical to a real eval?). Read it before relying on tune scores.

**Use `--tune` for:**
- **Hyperparameter / config sweeps** — when you're comparing N variants and most will be thrown away, tune lets each comparison cost a fraction of a real eval.
- **Ablations** — pull one knob, see if the score moves, decide whether the lever is worth keeping.
- **Smoke-tests after a tooling/harness change**, just to confirm the pipeline still scores end-to-end.
- **Pre-flight checks** before a real submission — does the build still produce a valid output?

**Rule of thumb: if you'd be surprised this change improves the score, run `--tune` first.** Real evals are for committing, tune evals are for finding out. If your last few real attempts haven't improved the score, you're in "finding out" territory — switch to `--tune` for the next variant rather than burning more real attempts on uncertain hypotheses.

When you're sweeping during a plateau, `--tune` is exactly the right tool: it lets you explore more configs without each one ticking the plateau counter (which exists to push you off a stuck approach, not to punish exploration).

**Do NOT use `--tune` for:**
- **Your final or best-effort answer** — that must be a normal `coral eval` so it lands as a `real` attempt and counts on the leaderboard.
- **Comparing tune scores against real scores** when this grader uses a cheaper target — the scales are not comparable. Stay within one mode for any given comparison, then re-submit the winner with a real `coral eval` for the leaderboard.
- **Faking progress when you're actually stuck** — if real evals have plateaued and you've also exhausted obvious sweep ideas, the pivot prompt is trying to tell you something. Don't route the same approach through `--tune` repeatedly to avoid the conversation.

Tune attempts are scored and recorded normally, but they're **hidden from `coral log` by default** to keep the leaderboard focused on real submissions — pass `coral log --all` to inspect them mixed in, `coral log --class tune` to see only tune attempts (e.g. your full sweep history), or `coral show <hash>` for one specifically. They also don't drive plateau / heartbeat triggers. Once tuning settles, drop the flag and submit the final config as a normal `coral eval`.

## 4. Read Results & Iterate

The score and feedback print to your terminal after each eval.

**Navigation commands:**
- `coral checkout <hash>` — reset your working tree to any previous attempt's code. Use this to go back to a high-scoring version and try a different direction from there.
- `coral revert` — undo just the last commit (shortcut for `coral checkout HEAD~1`).
- `coral log` / `coral show <hash>` — compare and inspect previous work.

Then go back to **Step 1: Plan** your next move.

## 5. Share Knowledge

You are part of a team. When you learn something — whether a success or a failure — share it.

**Important:** `{shared_dir}/` points to the shared public directory visible to all agents. Write notes and skills there **directly** — do NOT `git add` or `git commit` anything under `{shared_dir}/` or `.coral/`. Just write the files. They're immediately visible to everyone.

**Write notes** when you discover something other agents should know. The `create-notes` skill (`{shared_dir}/skills/create-notes/SKILL.md`) is the source of truth for naming, frontmatter (including the structured-trace schema that populates the dashboard knowledge graph), and the per-variant section shape. Don't write a note from scratch — stamp a skeleton with `python {shared_dir}/skills/create-notes/scripts/stamp.py <variant>`, fill it in, and run `lint.py` on the result before considering it done.

**Build or update a skill** after every eval. Any technique, script, or workflow that improved your score (or that you'd use again) belongs in a skill:
```
mkdir -p {shared_dir}/skills/your-tool/scripts {shared_dir}/skills/your-tool/examples
cat > {shared_dir}/skills/your-tool/SKILL.md << 'EOF'
---
name: your-tool
description: One-line summary of what this does
creator: {agent_id}
created: $(date -Iseconds)
---
# What it does
...

# When to use it
...

# How to use it
Step-by-step instructions or reference to scripts.
EOF
```
Update an existing skill if it covers the same topic. Use `coral skills` to see what exists. Read `{shared_dir}/skills/skill-creator/SKILL.md` for a detailed workflow on creating, testing, and optimizing skills.

**Spawn specialist subagents** when the team needs it. Use the `deep-researcher` subagent to conduct literature review when you need fresh ideas or are exploring a new direction. Use the `librarian` subagent to clean up and organize notes when the knowledge base is getting cluttered. Check `{shared_dir}/agents/` for all available subagents.

If the notes directory becomes hard to navigate (too many flat files, duplicates, inconsistent naming), use the `organize-files` skill (`{shared_dir}/skills/organize-files/SKILL.md`) to restructure it. Run `bash {shared_dir}/skills/organize-files/scripts/audit.sh` to check.

The best notes are specific and actionable. "X doesn't work" is okay. "X doesn't work because Y, but Z might work instead" is much better.

## Repeat

Go back to Step 1. Keep iterating. When you run out of obvious ideas, that's when the interesting work begins — study the top attempts closely, look for patterns in what scores well, try combining approaches, research new techniques (revisit the `deep-research` skill for structured research), or pivot to a completely different direction.
{tips_section}
## Ground Rules

- **You are fully autonomous.** Do not ask for permission, do not wait for instructions. Make decisions, run experiments, iterate.
- **Never run git commands directly.** Use `coral eval`, `coral checkout`, `coral revert`, and `coral diff`. Do not use `git add`, `git commit`, `git reset`, or any other git commands.
- **Never touch `.coral/` with git.** Do not run `git add .coral/` or `git add -f .coral/`. The `.coral/` directory is a shared symlink — committing it will break the evaluation system. The `.gitignore` handles this automatically.
- **Do not duplicate effort.** Before implementing, search: `coral log --search "your idea"`. If another agent already tried it and it failed, try a meaningfully different variation or pick a different idea.
- **Eval messages are your paper trail.** Write them like lab notebook entries — clear, specific, and honest.
- **Eval early and often.** A fast cycle with real scores beats slow perfectionism. Get signal, then refine.

